---
# ============================================================
# Baseline NetworkPolicies — cluster zero-trust
# ============================================================
# K3s enforces NetworkPolicy out of the box via its embedded kube-router
# network-policy controller (active by default alongside the Flannel CNI).
# No policies are shipped by default, so the pod network is otherwise flat:
# every pod can reach every pod, across all namespaces.
#
# This manifest installs a ZERO-TRUST cluster baseline: deny ALL ingress AND
# egress in two namespaces, then re-open only the minimal egress each system
# component needs. `kube-system` gets NO policy (see below). The Ceph operator
# namespace (ceph-csi-operator-system) is handled separately by
# 56-ceph-network-policies.yml.j2 (same pattern, co-located with the Ceph CSI
# group 50-56). Application namespaces use the same deny-all + targeted-allow
# pattern — see the ansible-k3s README "Securing a new namespace" tutorial.
#
# Why deny-all-both here (and not just ingress)? The previous baseline left
# egress open; zero-trust closes outbound too, so a compromised pod in these
# namespaces cannot phone home or scan the storage/api networks. Each allow
# below names exactly what its component legitimately needs.
#
# What is NOT affected / NOT enforced:
#   - kube-system:  no policy at all. Its critical components (CoreDNS, kube-proxy,
#                   metrics-server, Traefik, kube-vip) need broad connectivity and
#                   run partly hostNetwork; locking it down on K3s is risky and
#                   out of scope. Pods in OTHER namespaces still reach kube-dns
#                   because DNS egress is explicitly allowed below.
#   - Probes:       kubelet liveness/readiness probes (node-to-pod) are exempt
#                   from NetworkPolicy — node-originated traffic is not enforced.
#   - Admission     webhooks (cert-manager, metallb) are called by the kube-apiserver,
#                   which runs as a host process (not a pod) — that traffic is also
#                   node-originated and therefore exempt, so the deny-ingress below
#                   does NOT break webhook validation.
#   - hostNetwork:  kube-router does NOT enforce NP on hostNetwork pods. The MetalLB
#                   speakers run hostNetwork, so the metallb-system policy only
#                   applies to the controller (which is what we protect — it does
#                   leader election / watch / allocation), not to the speakers
#                   themselves. (The Ceph CSI node plugins are likewise hostNetwork;
#                   their namespace policy lives in 56-ceph-network-policies.yml.j2.)
# ============================================================

# 1. default — strict quarantine. A pod that lands here can only resolve DNS;
#    it cannot be reached and cannot reach anything else. Deploy real apps in a
#    dedicated namespace (see README), not in `default`.
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: default-deny-all
  namespace: default
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  policyTypes:
    - Ingress
    - Egress
---
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-dns-egress
  namespace: default
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  policyTypes:
    - Egress
  egress:
    - to:
        - namespaceSelector:
            matchLabels:
              kubernetes.io/metadata.name: kube-system
          podSelector:
            matchLabels:
              k8s-app: kube-dns
      ports:
        - protocol: UDP
          port: 53
        - protocol: TCP
          port: 53
---
# 2. metallb-system — deny all, then let the controller reach the API server
#    (leader election + watch) and DNS. Speakers run hostNetwork (not enforced);
#    the controller's webhook is served to the kube-apiserver (node-origin,
#    exempt — see header). Nothing else legitimately reaches MetalLB pods.
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: default-deny-all
  namespace: metallb-system
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  policyTypes:
    - Ingress
    - Egress
---
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-egress-kubeapi
  namespace: metallb-system
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  policyTypes:
    - Egress
  egress:
    - to:
        - ipBlock:
            cidr: {{ node_cidr }}
      ports:
        - protocol: TCP
          port: 6443
---
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-egress-dns
  namespace: metallb-system
spec:
  podSelector: {}
  policyTypes:
    - Egress
  egress:
    - to:
        - namespaceSelector:
            matchLabels:
              kubernetes.io/metadata.name: kube-system
          podSelector:
            matchLabels:
              k8s-app: kube-dns
      ports:
        - protocol: UDP
          port: 53
        - protocol: TCP
          port: 53
---
# Prometheus scrape allow (only if observability_enabled) — :9120 metrics
# (metricshttps, served over HTTPS with the webhook cert — NOT :7473) for BOTH the
# controller and the speaker, which both expose container port `metricshttps`:9120 with
# the same v0.16 bearer-token auth. podSelector matches `app: metallb` so it covers
# both components (controller: regular pod, enforced; speaker: hostNetwork, on which
# kube-router does NOT enforce NP — see header — so the speaker is reachable via the
# hostNetwork bypass regardless, but selecting it here is belt-and-suspenders in case
# that ever changes).
{% if observability_enabled | bool %}
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: allow-ingress-from-prometheus
  namespace: metallb-system
spec:
  podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      app: metallb
  policyTypes:
    - Ingress
  ingress:
    - from:
        - namespaceSelector:
            matchLabels:
              kubernetes.io/metadata.name: {{ observability_namespace }}
          podSelector:
            matchLabels:
              app.kubernetes.io/name: prometheus
      ports:
        - protocol: TCP
          port: 9120
{% endif %}
